Anyone with alters n things have any idea what sort of space the child alters should have? Many of us have spaces to be when we're not fronting, but a lot of the child alters sort of just cease to exist. I think they deserve a space, they're good kids.

Like when the body was 6 or younger. As a child's sense of identity can come to exist, she's the oldest host in the system, and there are a lot of Claires around, different versions. Like how there are two of me. But she's adjusting, and we're all proud of her.

We're all at such different ages. I'm 32 but the body isn't even that old, that's just how old I was born to be and will be forever, like my sister Caroline, who's 19. We're twins, and the body was 14 when we were born.
  But Claire is legitimately 8. She was made... so young.

The child alters are still very confused and generally uncommunicative in the system but I think even Claire- our oldest host- is gradually coming to term with things, I think. She's like, what? 8?  What an absolute champ, very proud of her. Mature beyond her lived years.

I think since the system in general got on board with the fact we're a system we've become a lot less erratic. We share memories more, and we've all become more whole. Even fragments like Sergio have a say in things, I think that's wholesome.

@autonecrophila You deserve to live your best life, and your best life isn't one tied to an addiction. Everyone says the longer you live away from a bad habit the less you miss it, the best thing to do is not lie to yourself and think you can quit when you're gonna do it a little bit

stand up, make food, and I clean the dishes before they go mouldy! Who could do that?
  Everyone. Everyone but me. I just assumed everyone found it equally as difficult. I even knew I had ADHD since I was a kid but I had no idea how bad it was because I could scrape by school.

I never said I struggled, I never even thought to. I assumed existing was as difficult for everyone else as it was for me- why would people kick a fuss at doing chores if they didn't have the same sense of difficulty as I did?
  Every day I'm amazed at how I can get dressed,

If you struggle with ADHD I highly recommend getting properly diagnosed and trying the meds. I've said it before and I'll say it again: you will not regret recovering. Even if it doesn't go well, the experience is extremely useful to have. Once the extreme hunger fades you suddenly realize how deep you were in your disorder, and if you relapse you keep what you learned.

Don't get me wrong, i fucking hate having an ED, this shit is still actively fucking up my life.  But it's nice that I have the headspace to look after myself a little better, and right now full recovery just isn't something I can do right now.

I made a lot of mistakes when I first recovered (very DIY) hence why I'm here now, but I think I prefer this half-state over full "recovery" or full relapse. I generally know how to jolt myself out of my worst habits so I won't get caught. Although, I do feel very trapped.

I'm not even talking about like, recovery rhetoric "you deserve food" kind of stuff, I mean I just got really, really into nutrition and psychology and now I know what I was doing wrong. I know what I was doing to my body and mind, I know why I do the things I do (ish)

I've been in such a weird place this past year, this twilight zone of being kinda-relapsed but kinda not? I really thought when I relapsed I'd just go straight back to how I was, but it turns out all the stuff I learned in recovery has really helped me not die this year

General task management:
 I write a lot of lists. I don't make them extensive, they're just general things I want to get done. In the winter I usually have one or two tasks a day aside from my routine, it doesn't mean I complete them but it's better https://t.co/KrmV99P4pz

Laundry in the winter:
- I try to do laundry before it runs out because i've ended up wearing the last set of clothes for a week straight
- Having more underwear than other clothes gives you time
- I sort the laundry and leave it in piles on the floor, often putting one load in

Showering in winter:
- I buy 2-in-1 shampoo/conditioner
- I use that to clean most of my body, too
- Often when I shower I don't actually clean, I just sit in the stream. It's better than nothing
- After showering I lay down on my towel and air-dry

Stocking and finances
  Check your bank account NOW. Figure out your in/out, make a general budget, and stock up on foods and miscellaneous items like toilet roll, toothpaste, etc NOW. Things you buy now are one less task you need to preform during the Dark Days.

bed. If you have a sofa, live there instead of your bed, it'll make your sleep schedule more solid. If you have no place other than a bed, find a way of distinguishing your Day bed and Night bed, like by facing the opposite direction during the day than when you sleep.

to wipe sweat and grime off my body (ik it's gross but it works)
- Deodorant (a good deodorant is crucial, I use Rock Face)
- Put on clean clothes
- Toilet
- Brush teeth (or mouthwash for now, you can try brushing ur teeth later)

Then you find a place to exist which isn't your

what else you do, you stick to THAT routine. It doesn't have to be in the morning, but it's a daily sequence of events. Once you have a routine solidified it's much easier to maintain it during the winter. My routine is as follows:
- Wake up
- Take off clothes

Bear in mind that you will crave carbs during the winter, and carbs are essential in producing serotonin, so this isn't the time to go keto.

If I have the freezer space, I'll try to make bulk foods to freeze so I can reheat them in the winter. Otherwise I stick to things like:
- Microwave rice
- Ready meals
- Easy meal replacement shakes
- Pre-sliced vegetables and jars of sauce to put on them
